				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Keeping aggro... <a name="41182"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">May 21 04 6:19 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>
<br />
As long as you're not main slower, and sometimes on ldon's
<br />
you can get away with it even if you are, use assonance for
<br />
slow instead of requiem.  I actually open with it.  Then, as
<br />
the mob is getting back to group, I'll land 1 chant with drums,
<br />
equipped, then the mob hits me, I'll switch to 2 weapons and
<br />
start beating it.  As I see chanter or shammy slow land I'll use
<br />
slam (i'm a barb bard) and bellow, my 2nd chant is also about
<br />
to land.
<br />

<br />
With that initial start up I'm usually able to keep aggro over
<br />
anyone who's not purposefully trying to take it (i.e. chain
<br />
snare or stun).  I can usually get away with playing zek, muse
<br />
and marr for the rest of the fight, which isn't long anyway.
<br />

<br />
But the real key is assonance, and landing it if at all possible
<br />
*before* the main slower does.  The closest thing to snap
<br />
aggro a bard has available is landing assonance + slam + 
<br />
bellow.
<br />

<br />
'Stuce</span></td>
